  "text": "Our final goal was to prevent the memory impairment in NI rats by pharmacologically inhibiting microglia. To do this, we used the microglial inhibitor MINO, which we administered via oral gavage to mimic the clinical route of administration and to avoid the visceral irritation that occurs following intraperitoneal injection (our unpublished observations). In our first experiment, rats from each neonatal treatment group were injected with LPS as adults, and fear conditioned 24 h later (Fig. 7a) . Rats also received a loading dose of MINO (50 mg/kg) or its vehicle (water) in a volume of 5 ml/kg via oral gavage 12 h before LPS injection, and received a second dose (water or 25 mg/kg) 1 h before injection. This dosing regimen significantly decreases proinflammatory cytokine production by microglia [CITATION_1] . Contextual memory was assessed 72 h after conditioning in one-half of the animals in each group (n ϭ 10/group MINO treated, and n ϭ 8/group water treated). In the remaining animals (n ϭ 8 -10/ Figure 3 . NI rats exhibit decreased neuronal inhibition within the HP compared with controls. Rats treated with PBS or E. coli on P4 were injected as adults with SAL or LPS, and 24 h later received Fear Conditioning or Shock only (n ϭ 8/group). Brains were collected 2 h later, and target genes were assessed. a, CD200 and its receptor (CD200R) were reduced overall in NI rats compared with controls in the fear conditioned group (*p Ͻ 0.01 for both), whereas only CD200R was significantly decreased by LPS (**p Ͻ 0.02). b, There were no neonatal group differences in CD200 or CD200R in the Shock only group; however, both genes were decreased by LPS (**p Ͻ 0.02). c, d, Fractalkine receptor (CX3CR1) but not its ligand was reduced overall in NI rats in both Fear Conditioned and Shock only groups. (*p Ͻ 0.05 for all, compared with PBS). Error bars indicate SEM. group), brains were collected 2 h after fear conditioning to assess IL-1␤ protein within the HP. For freezing behavior, there was a significant group by drug interaction (F (1,35) ϭ 7.3; p ϭ 0.01). Freezing was lower in NI plus water rats compared with all other groups (p Ͻ 0.03 for all), and MINO given before LPS completely reversed this (Fig. 7b) . For IL-1␤ protein, there was a significant interaction as well (F (1,35) ϭ 4.9; p ϭ 0.034); NI rats had higher IL-1␤ concentrations than controls when treated with water before LPS (p ϭ 0.01), whereas MINO given before LPS prevented this increase (Fig. 7d, left panel) .",
